commit_message:
Adds support for several applications in single Pod

Kubernetes doesn't allow to add containers to a Pod that
is already deployed. With this change old pods will be deleted
and either new pod created which will include new container
or Replication Controller will be modified (before Pod delete
so that updated Pods be created instead)

Also now Pods are created only when replica number set to 0.
Otherwise Pods created by ReplicationController alone.

Change-Id: I8552793f39083de47ad07e7013dedb72e0550885
Closes-Bug: #1444208

commit_message:
Fixes replication controller deletion

KubernetesCluster method to delete RC was using incorrect
property and there was a typo in execution plan making it
fail on validation

Also renames destroy* methods to delete* methods to match
Kubernetes terms

Change-Id: I2ff71679deeb5ad3692fcc1a5fcfed8fa0e8d94f
Closes-Bug: #1443857

commit_message:
Use different passwords for admin and keystone users

Currently, the keystone service user is created w/ the same password as
the admin user.  This change updates the keystone service user creation
to be done w/ the value of keystone_service_password instead of
keystone_auth_admin_password.

Change-Id: Icc643c3a79ca5f58b53651b90695adafb83532e5
Closes-Bug: #1443955

commit_message:
Update tempest to use admin user

Currently, keystone tasks in the tempest role use a combination of
keystone_service_user_name and keystone_auth_admin_password, which only
works due to bug #1443955.  This change updates the tempest role to
use keystone_auth_admin_token / keystone_service_adminurl when
performing keystone actions, which is the same pattern that exists in
other roles.

Additionally, we update os_tempest/templates/tempest.conf.j2 to use
keystone_admin_user_name / keystone_admin_tenant_name instead of
keystone_service_user_name / keystone_service_tenant_name.  This fixes
the keystone_service_user_name / keystone_auth_admin_password
discrepancy while also being more logical than using the actual
keystone service user / password within tempest.conf.

Closes-Bug: #1443962
Change-Id: I63391095557501693bbe663aba3219ca5c292057

commit_message:
Add devstack-vagrant to QA

This commit adds the devstack-vagrant repo to the QA program. This
was another repo which was missed during the devstack qa merge last
year.

Change-Id: Ie86b894607ada24611768ba475cc292bae0c809b

commit_message:
Add support for ArchivePolicy Rule Endpoints

The goal of this is to expose an end point where
user could define an archive policy rule mapping
to a metric pattern. There could be multiple rules
defined. This rule is used when a metric is created
to automatically assign a policy to the metric based
on matching pattern defined in the rule.

There will be a subsequent patch that leverages this
in the metric api.

Change-Id: I8a71f25fe25c4be20d14d695c52fa7cb6efcb14b

commit_message:
Pass correct port ID back to RPC caller

The previous response to get_device_details calls was returning
whatever the caller requested as the port_id in the response.
This was only correct in the case where the port_id was used
directly. In cases where device names were passed in, there was
no way to retrieve the full port ID.

This corrects that behavior by using the port ID from the database
and adds tests to ensure the behavior remains correct.

Closes-Bug: #1443714
Change-Id: Ibfc7b6659a29e892dfe6e83bd9340feb40e920dd

commit_message:
Add network.yml monitoring playbook

To monitor the number of open connections a new monitoring playbook has
been added called network.yml. This playbook will need to be run as
part of the deployment when the other monitoring playbooks are used.

This playbook will create a new alarm that will alert when > 90% of
nf_conntrack_max is reached by nf_conntrack_count. The data is
collected using the conntrack_count.py plugin in the rcbops-maas repo.

Closes-Bug: #1439604

commit_message:
Clean authorization mocking in tests

Remove remaining 'execute_wo_tests' as now authorization is
mocked in all tests by default.
Changed mocking from 'auth_client' to 'auth_required' to make
it simple to change in tests (now it's just a matter of changing
boolean).

Change-Id: Icfd0ef3058918e1578a21429f84a1583eddd3a8e
Closes-Bug: #1443279

commit_message:
Update packages earlier

Turns out that updating packages last causes some pretty
non-intuitive behaviour if you are trying to pin a package
to a specific version. Lets just update the base RPMs first...
subsequent installations should install the most updated version
anyways (unless they are pinned).

Also moves the package-installs script from the 00 step to 01 so
we can do the update first.

Co-Authored-By: Ben Nemec <bnemec@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I962046cc6048e852e6582fbc579f88bb73e23fdd

commit_message:
Not call dockerclient-api del none exist container

At some case the container will had record in magnum
db but it doesn't exist in fact.May be docker create
container fail or end-user delete it by docker api
otherwise magnum api.

Change-Id: Idc41eaedbd13250d25c33bc3d81f6503b84c574e
Closes-Bug: #1443215

This is intended to add functionality to python-glanceclient to support
Catalog Index Service by exposing commands for searching and managing

Change-Id: I4c9b6e26a72d8ef3a48fc1644503bd539f397999
Implements: blueprint catalog-index-service-client

commit_message:
Support CIS service in glanceclient

This is intended to add functionality to python-glanceclient to support
Catalog Index Service by exposing commands for searching and managing
data stored within it.

Change-Id: I4c9b6e26a72d8ef3a48fc1644503bd539f397999

- the log is mostly useless to debug an application
- the log is only needed when debugging Oslo Messaging itself
- the most important information of the log is the request identifier, but this information is usually logged anyway by applications
- applications are run in debug mode for testing / pre-integration environments
- According to Mehdi, a developer can easy reintroduce this log locally when debugging Oslo Messaging
- If a bug can only be reproduced on gates, it's possible to write a patch with the log to debug

commit_message:
Remove amqp driver 'unpacked content' logging

Different OpenStack processes log that line when idle, but it doesn't
offer actionable information to developers or users. Ideally process
logs should be silent when idle, even in debug mode.

Here's a sample:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/201371/

Change-Id: Ib4f63d590a6f5ed295fae12dac12897007b12879

commit_message:
Extract cinder-client response to log request IDs

Extract cinder-client response and log the mapping of request IDs
between nova and cinder if response is a tuple object.

This is a prerequisite for cinder-spec 'Return request ID to caller'
(Ic65281f8edb6064d10b35c335d268fe3672a898e) to be completed.

blueprint: log-request-id-mappings
Change-Id: Iefd8a5a7cb7d82cc56ce485d2ca5ff255a71ffef

commit_message:
Make SoftwareDeployments work for non-CREATE actions

Currently we only create the deployment if the actions list includes
CREATE, but its valid to create e.g DELETE only deployments, which
curently won't work.  So determine whether to create the deployment
on the resource_id instead of via the action, which resolves this problem.

Change-Id: Ia563f4130c31baa4dcee3be3786ea3c49b6bad98
Closes-Bug: #1444087

commit_message:
Fix requirements to fit for gate test

The requirements project has updated
https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/global-requirements.txt

which can cause failure for gate job

http://logs.openstack.org/74/173374/3/gate/gate-magnum-python27/a382639/console.html

So we need to update local requirements before integrate
to requirements project.

Closes-Bug: #1444230

Change-Id: I74e4bf0cf3e4451bc87abd5e4c19e9901d16e05a

commit_message:
Remove redirection from stdout to dump.log

  Since FileHandler is added to shotgun's logger, there's no need in
  redirection to stdout.

Related to change: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/170805
Closes-Bug: 1318516

Change-Id: Ibc06dab96c8595163ece003402735c7a33ecefd0

commit_message:
Use 'node' terminology instead of 'item' terminology

Since graphs are composed of 'nodes' it seems more
appropriate to use that terminology (which is known
to people with graph experience) instead of the non
descriptive and/or standard 'item' terminology.

Change-Id: I04a4521386d3cdf7e58fb9fa8cf26c00443c2cf6

commit_message:
Turn 'check_who' into a decorator

This helper function seems to be more pretty/nice as
a decorator that is used uniformly instead of repeated
calling into it from needed functions.

commit_message:
Make resolution/retry strategies more clear and better

This adds a separate method which is used to locate the
action and handler callback that will be used to resolve
the failure. This also adjusts the consultation of the
parent retry (if any) to ensure that we handle the no
parent retry case correctly.

Once a decision has been made; return it and add logging
that shows what is being activated and how many nodes were
affected by the resolution strategy (which can be useful to
know during debugging).

Change-Id: I28101765fce000dd7c56b7c3a1fbcf1a4315799b

[{'created': '2015-04-14 21:29:00.000000000', 'message': 'rpc_backend: simplify parameters

Since Icehouse, there is no need to specify the whole Python namespace
for the backends.
We can now use keywords like "rabbit", "qpid" or "zmq".

This patch maintains backward compatibility with previous default
parameters in case someone overrides it with the default parameter.

Source: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/rpc.py#L48-L55

Closes-bug: #1405656

Change-Id: I23d1331e047a99cac3f4939f83de190275ca1236
(cherry picked from commit 9fdcb01c96cc085f8a57a855bd70cc8129699a6f)
'}]
commit_message:
rpc_backend: simplify parameters

Since Icehouse, there is no need to specify the whole Python namespace
for the backends.
We can now use keywords like "rabbit", "qpid" or "zmq".

This patch maintains backward compatibility with previous default
parameters in case someone overrides it with the default parameter.

Source: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/rpc.py#L48-L55

Closes-bug: #1405656

Change-Id: I23d1331e047a99cac3f4939f83de190275ca1236
(cherry picked from commit 9fdcb01c96cc085f8a57a855bd70cc8129699a6f)

commit_message:
IPv6 support for migration check.

This enables the use of the '::0' IPv6 address for the vncserver_listen
parameter.

    class { 'nova::compute::libvirt':
      vncserver_listen         => '::0',
      migration_support        => true,
    }

Change-Id: Iec69a82c6a7bbf1b0f7364e87e1e3e37a876be9a
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652
(cherry picked from commit 70d33d7a687fc06fbb22674a678703d11717b693)

commit_message:
Clean up keystone provider methods and tests

This patch does some cleanup by:
 - Removing unused methods such as remove_warnings and auth_keystone and corresponding tests
 - Moved the retry test into openstack_spec.rb and updated it to correspond to the new syntax
 - Moved the class reset method into keystone_spec.rb since that is the only place it is used

Change-Id: I9bea06680ae7b6cc68cb9df83dbcaa62ac5d2aa9
(cherry picked from commit 068c9adb94bf530b9b68f4783f9d0af01274a4e2)

Nova is able to talk to a read-only database for some tables so it
improves the scalability of MySQL server and reduce the access to the
server in charge of writes.

More documentation: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Slave_usage

Change-Id: I1d44332acb381b11d90b63535d274f535be26d55
(cherry picked from commit 1b2725b5518ba2fd422e3ea954efae4a763f9878)
'}]
commit_message:
Database: add slave_connection support

Nova is able to talk to a read-only database for some tables so it
improves the scalability of MySQL server and reduce the access to the
server in charge of writes.

More documentation: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Slave_usage

Change-Id: I1d44332acb381b11d90b63535d274f535be26d55
(cherry picked from commit 1b2725b5518ba2fd422e3ea954efae4a763f9878)

Add Nova Aggregate support

Bring nova aggregate and availability zones support into puppet-nova.

  - Handle nil values and 0 lengths (Aimon Bustardo)
  - Remove extraneous whitespace on aggregate-create (Aimon Bustardo)

Implements: blueprint aggregate-handling

Change-Id: I9125d573a6a3cf4d444300d3570c4ab394c4ecd8
(cherry picked from commit 08578c920e5582a1817e6c07858dd4b71d4f0b84)

[{'created': '2015-04-14 22:29:03.000000000', 'message': "Fix ipv6 support

There is issue with ipv6 where address has to be in brackets, this causes the
underlying ruby TCPSocket to fail. Net::HTTP.new will fail without brackets on
joining the ipv6 address with :port or passing brackets to TCPSocket. It was
found that if we use Net::HTTP.start with url.hostname the incriminated code
won't be hit.

Change-Id: If9b2b629b701c4a4c2794c3b4af584bcfc47fc2d
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652
(cherry picked from commit 287508083b7bc61013c19b793252496d7f76d0d2)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix ipv6 support

There is issue with ipv6 where address has to be in brackets, this causes the
underlying ruby TCPSocket to fail. Net::HTTP.new will fail without brackets on
joining the ipv6 address with :port or passing brackets to TCPSocket. It was
found that if we use Net::HTTP.start with url.hostname the incriminated code
won't be hit.

Change-Id: If9b2b629b701c4a4c2794c3b4af584bcfc47fc2d
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652
(cherry picked from commit 287508083b7bc61013c19b793252496d7f76d0d2)

commit_message:
New option replace_password for keystone_user

Adds a new option replace_password, which defaults
to 'True' for all keystone_user objects, that
has the effect of enforcing the password of a given
keystone_user. If this is disabled, the user may change
his or her password at a later time and not be reset
by the keystone Puppet module.

Ported from CID: I4bd59f233273374545953f16c7843488148096d6

Change-Id: Ib61128556fed816916af944ed7576e916081da07
Closes-Bug: #1400798
(cherry picked from commit 6db9a52cde33a60b5cec85e5bdee8119deca4973)

commit_message:
Let WebOb read the body of a PATCH when creating docs

webob had a bug wherein the body was not read on a PATCH. A pull
request was submitted:

    https://github.com/Pylons/webob/pull/184

and a new release with that change was released recently, breaking
fresh 'tox -e docs' jobs.

This changeset just requires the working WebOb. This may present
packaging issues, so tidier solutions welcome.

Closes-Bug: #1444160
Change-Id: I650a3ca3ae8381c556457c4504460c2b7f8a8d60

"I think the intention here is to have separate life cycles for the two jobs, for instance so that we can make the non-dvr job voting sooner than the non-dvr job. Having said that, if you guys think that long-term we should only have a single multi-node job and that is DVR, then we might as well take the bull by the horn and start that now. commit_message:
Enable DVR for Neutron aiopcpu job

This will make the Neutron's aiopcpu job consistent
with the settings for the nova-networkt aiopcpu job
where multi-node is enabled.

Depends-On: Id8d16877f09a1128c10f5c52438f6b7726c01f8e

Change-Id: Ic90617665feea513a1d0a43850c8e98b33c7a5a0

commit_message:
Fix tests to work with requests<2.3

The tests didn't pass with requests<2.3 because of the cookies
monkey-patching.

To test this, make sure the requests library in your tox venv is
the right level:

 $ .tox/py27/bin/pip install -U "requests<2.3"

Then run the tests.

Closes-Bug: 1442919
Change-Id: Ie93906ba2370dada2386a50ae2137337ccf98f10
(cherry picked from commit a335b7f6f2577f06cead7b7acbfa07dd771a94b9)

commit_message:
Fix three bugs in webhook

1. Add API version number which is omitted where generating
   webhook url.
2. Encrypt credential before store webhook so the encrypted
   credential rather then original one will be stored into DB.
3. If auth_url is not provided in credential, auth_url of
   senlin service context will be used for authentication.

Change-Id: I5573de3349cb7f8582970c69b9392e5fd35ae281

commit_message:
Add helper method to find OVSDB row by external_id's

The user of this method can find the first row that its external_ids
column matches all of the input dictionary <key,value> pairs.
This enables the user to use the method with partiall external id's but
still find the first matching row

Change-Id: I5b0211fbeda4f6a1d9c88f19fba586c56e485476
Closes-Bug: #1443259

commit_message:
Ensure security group body does not always include description

The description value for a security group is optional, and
doesn't need to be included if it's doesn't have a value.

commit_message:
Add unit tests for log_curl_request

Add 5 new tests that check if log_curl_request method produces proper
curl commands and add again an old test checking this method for
unicode support.

Change-Id: I64caad18d537d727835f3a7ada010ec45b20638a
Closes-Bug: 1174339

commit_message:
Adds DVR functional test for multi-external networks

This patch adds DVR functional test for multiple
external networks related to FIP namespace.
This test validates that FIP namespaces are created
based on the external networks associated with the
router.

Change-Id: I0f8cd352e83f8c2f04bf420a8b0dd6407de6b5ce

commit_message:
Persist parent_resource_name and make sure it's available

We are persisting for a number of reasons:
- so we don't have to pass this through ever rpc call
- the API exposes parent_resource (currently always None as
  it is not persisted)

Closes-bug: #1438978

commit_message:
Update man pages for the Kilo release

The current man pages for keystone-manage don't include commands relating to
Fernet setup, or the domain configuration upload.

Change-Id: Ifd208151470d8d39d3d4851557e45dc12d1a577b
Closes-Bug: #1441300

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-15 01:53:36.000000000', 'message': 'Fix incorrect setting in WebSSO documentation

The WebSSO documentation describes the WEBSSO_INITIAL_CHOICE setting,
but it then shows an example with the incorrect configuration setting
name (WEBSSO_CHOICES).  This corrects the example.

Change-Id: I2cd261f2377da3738e1b0befe62166dac5c49a2f
'}]
commit_message:
Fix incorrect setting in WebSSO documentation

The WebSSO documentation describes the WEBSSO_INITIAL_CHOICE setting,
but it then shows an example with the incorrect configuration setting
name (WEBSSO_CHOICES).  This corrects the example.

Change-Id: I2cd261f2377da3738e1b0befe62166dac5c49a2f

commit_message:
Remove the export creation during volume creation for migration

Since create_export was moved from create_volume to
initialize_connection, the migrate_volume part should change
accordingly.

Change-Id: I42637c5d861670fb125e78918c2b5b2b13ea43d4
Closes-bug: #1278289

commit_message:
Fix broken test_policy_IO_override test

Since the existing check depends on how quickly the test
passes, it causes to the unpredictable behavior and may break
the test.

This commit removes the unnecessary dependency on the
current time and leaves only the check that timestamp is 
greater than 0.

Change-Id: I3321e9aba0df52cb78523710b26f310f35801674
Closes-Bug: #1441599

(1 comment)

I mostly like it, but the inclusion of version strings in /info seems like a bad idea to me. Clients should use "/v1"; we've always said that, and letting clients discover some other strings that work in place of "/v1" does not sound like a good idea. Imagine a cluster where some client was using "/placeholder"; you don't want to announce to the world that your cluster lets you use "/placeholder" as a version. That's something you want to keep a secret, just between you and the client's lazy author.'}, {'account_id': 5600, 'date': '2015-04-07 19:19:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 15090, 'date': '2015-04-09 13:30:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-04-09 17:30:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Sam

Why do you want configurable constraints that are secret? (aside from the fact that the whole constraints loading would need to be refactored to enable that) I don't really see how that helps users. This patch is putting a limit on what's a valid request from a user, so I think that the valid values should be discoverable by the client."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-04-09 21:15:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I'm just trying to imagine a case where, as a client, I benefit from knowing what extra version strings are accepted by the cluster.

If I'm constructing a path to an object and I need a version string to put in there, I don't need to go digging around in /info to find that out. I can (and should!) just use "v1". That always works.

If I've got a legacy client that uses something like "/swift", then I don't need to go digging around in /info to find a valid version string because I clearly don't care about what's valid or not - I stuck some crap in a string and it worked once, so I shipped it! Now it's the cluster operator's problem.

The rule is simple: just use "v1". If you need an exception due to a legacy client, procure a bottle of your cluster operator's favorite liquor and attempt to exchange it for an exception in the config file.

Telling clients about exceptions will lead to clients using the exceptions for no rational reason. Imagine a cluster with valid versions "/v1", "/v1.0", and "/squirrel". There is a nonempty subset of client authors who will look at that list, say "heh, squirrel", and then proceed to type /-s-q-u-i-r-r-e-l into their code because it amuses them to do so. If we don't tell them about exceptions, they'll type in /-v-1, just like everyone else, and their application will be better for it.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-04-09 22:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

If an app developer sees that /squirrel is a valid version, then they can only use that for the cluster they are actually using. If they are using just one swift cluster, then who cares? If the app is running against multiple swift clusters, then it will need to support the subset of versions that all of the target swift clusters support, ie "v1".


That being said, since we don't actually have any API version other than v1 today, I can understand keeping it hidden for now. But hidden and configurable isn't something the code supports. Sam, can you work up a patch for that?'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-04-10 06:38:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Looks good, tests need to be fixed.

If an OP wants their cluster to use squirrel, then they can go for their life.. but if they stray from the defaults then they make it hard to be compatible to other clusters.. but that's there problem not ours :P

But if Sam wants to go fix it, go right ahead :)"}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-04-10 07:59:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-04-10 08:01:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

[{'created': '2015-03-27 23:01:28.000000000', 'message': "Don't let api version be a suggestion

I *really* hope ('v1', 'v1.0', '1', '1.0') is enough to keep us from
breaking clients we care about?  Can anyone think of others?

The proxy app will either return 404 if get_controller raises a
ValueError, or 412 if it can't match to a controller - which is the
current behavior for a number of paths like '/v1'.

We could standardize on 412, except that's not really what that
status is for.  We could standardize on 404, but that's even more
change to existing behavior.  Maybe this is a reasonable compromise?

Change-Id: I5ab6e236544378abf2eab562ab759513d09bc256

"}, {'created': '2015-03-30 18:02:28.000000000', 'message': 'Check if REST API version is valid

Swift doesn't check if the used API version is valid. Currently there is only
one valid REST API version, but that might change in the future.

This patch enforces "v1" as the version string when accessing account,
containers and objects. So far this is the only valid version string; others
(like "v1.0") are not known to be used when accessing accounts, containers or
objects.

The list of accepted version strings can be manually overriden using a
comma-separated list in swift.conf to make this backward-compatible. The
constraint loader has been modified slightly to accept strings as well as
integers.

The proxy app will either return 404 if get_controller raises a
ValueError, or 412 if it can't match to a controller - which is the
current behavior for a number of paths like '/v1'.

We could standardize on 412, except that's not really what that
status is for. We could standardize on 404, but that's even more
change to existing behavior. Maybe this is a reasonable compromise?

Co-Authored-By: Christian Schwede <christian.schwede@enovance.com>

Closes Bug #1437442

Change-Id: I5ab6e236544378abf2eab562ab759513d09bc256

commit_message:
Check if REST API version is valid

Swift doesn't check if the used API version is valid. Currently there
is only one valid REST API version, but that might change in the
future.

This patch enforces "v1" or "v1.0" as the version string when accessing
account, containers and objects.

The list of accepted version strings can be manually overridden using a
comma-separated list in swift.conf to make this backward-compatible.
The constraint loader has been modified slightly to accept strings as
well as integers.

Any request to an account, container, and object which does not
provide the correct version string will get a 400 BadRequest response.

The allowed api versions are by default excluded from /info.

Co-Authored-By: Christian Schwede <christian.schwede@enovance.com>
Co-Authored-By: John Dickinson <me@not.mn>

Closes Bug #1437442

Change-Id: I5ab6e236544378abf2eab562ab759513d09bc256

commit_message:
Add lowest option to swift-recon disk usage output

Currently there is a "--top" option when running swift-recon for
disk usage stats. This option lists the x disks with the highest
disk usage in descending order.

This feature adds a "--lowest" option which does the opposite and
lists the y disks with lowest disk usage in ascending order.

Have also updated the docs section with --top and --lowest options

Change-Id: Ic15d407fe010a31995c2bdd9fb88548a1057f569

commit_message:
Fix assertEqual in test_volume.py in correct order of params

AssertEqual/assertDictMatch is called with the wrong order of
parameters in many parts of test_volume.py. This patch fix them
all for test_volume.py.

Change-Id: I2ffb3a928710eb22eac9fc3afb6c2e38dc9903ce

commit_message:
Make group on /var/log/nova OS specific

On Ubuntu the group defaults to adm on /var/log/nova, on RH systems it
should be nova. Make it OS specific so it doesn't get re-assigned.

Change-Id: I989fd7888b7d509ac766afdb1bac6d3876f69542
Closes-Bug: #1267573
(cherry picked from commit be874ff0eb3479d2887ccc22d81c614e6b54352f)

commit_message:
Data structs declared with constructor replaced with literal

Changes:
  - list() declarations replaced with []
  - dict() declarations replaced with {}
  - Added N351 to hacking for literal rule along with checks, test hacking, and to readme
  - Minor fix to incorrect path in hacking guidelines pointing to test_hacking.py

Change-Id: Ie7b9201d61b6f2024217b6f4117605eb52fa916a
Closes-Bug: #1437515

commit_message:
timeutils: avoid passing leap second to datetime

Python datetime module does not support leap seconds [1]. The best thing
we can do without switching API to using another time module is to
avoid passing leap seconds to underlying python module.

Note: next leap second is scheduled for June 30 [2].

[1]: http://bugs.python.org/issue23574
[2]: http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/01/08/computer-chaos-feares/21433363/

Closes-Bug: #1427212
Change-Id: I7ffd8121cb20f3742e8e9cd7d4b8f0f15fa6ca9a
(cherry picked from commit c50d8161ac251ee0c9cad6012bc7ceab4f899d6f)

commit_message:
Implement cleaning/zapping for the agent driver

Adds get_clean_steps and execute_clean_steps for the agent. Also
implements prepare and tear_down for cleaning to ensure the agent
is booted during cleaning. These bits should be factored out to
the boot interface when that merges in L.

Adds checks for cleaning steps in the heartbeat handler.

Adds parameters to the dhcp functions to pass in VIFs instead
of relying on the cached ones in the Ironic port objects. As
cleaning can start before Nova can unplug those ports, we
should ignore the cached VIFs and use the ones we create.

Changes _do_next_clean_step to acquire a lock on its own so
cleaning from do_node_tear_down and continue_cleaning both
work.

Implements blueprint implement-cleaning-states
Change-Id: Ia2500ed5afb72058b4c5e8f41307169381cbce48
Depends-on: Ic38de10668c97648d073fdf9a3afc59712057849

envlist option defaults to the list of all environments

Add missed env to envlist so we can use `tox -l` to list
all environments defined.

commit_message:
genenv generated invalid variable

NEUTRON_SHARED_SECRET was being generated incorrectly.  It had a colon
at the front, which causes nova not to operate.

Change-Id: Id0d9390fa60b3d946513098fed394aaba3a53c70

commit_message:
Set Neutron api_workers to $API_WORKERS

Devstack sets the number of API workers for several other projects to
the value in the variable $API_WORKERS.  Do the same for Neutron's
API.

Closes-Bug: #1432189
Change-Id: I7ede29430923b0983b20ab27d9f3b7244deaa477
Depends-On: I4d76baf68b014fc80693f53874734783089abda2

Realized that I did not capture what we talked about in IRC here so doing that now.

We should use a single overlay network topology for both neutron and nova network. This is both for simplicity of setup in devstack-gate and because it should be possible in the real world to use a common network topology when say migrating from nova network to neutron.

We may need to update the existing overlay topology that is used by nova network to accomodate neutron but we should have only one.

We do think the current topology with two L2 networks with an interface on each compute node for each L2 network is sufficient for neutron as well. So ideally we don't even need to change the existing setup. However, it has come out that the use of flat and public as the network names may be confusing. We can rename them to something more appropriate."}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2015-04-08 05:39:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

Please see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171714 for some updates that make this almost work.

Basically I hard enabled DVR so that we test DVR with this change, fixed a bug enabling q-l3 on the subnode, enabled q-fwaas on the subnode because we enable it on the controller node, enabled q-meta on the subnode because that makes cloud-init work.

But the major change is to make the overlay gre bridge function generic enough for both neutron and nova-net. I did this by using the ovs gre bridge because devstack doesn't support setting up br-ex with a port attached. It expects you to do the port attachment so we go ahead and do that. Also, nova net is just fine with it (according to one test run so need more data).

Finally we do need some help from devstack to properly set up routing for the floating ip network between nodes. With nova-net we do this by defining the floating ip network to be 172.24.5.0/24 then we assign 172.24.4.1/23 to the controller's public interface and 172.24.4.2/23 to the compute subnode. This makes packets bound for the floating ip network route properly between the hypervisors. Unfortunately devstack clears out that config but it does set 172.24.5.1/24 on the controller's br-ex it just doesn't set 172.24.5.2/24 on the compute subnode.

Either devstack should leave our 172.24.4.0/23 addresses alone or it should set the IP on the subnode's br-ex for us. I have a slight preference for it setting the ip on br-ex for us since it already does that for the controller."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-04-09 06:42:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 24.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-09 08:00:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Verified+1

'}, {'created': '2015-04-10 06:27:12.000000000', 'message': "Add Neutron DVR aiopcpu support

Configure the subnode to run the extra services required
for Neutron DVR, like the L3 agent (in 'dvr' mode).

The data path between the controller and the subnode is
established via a tunnel created using OVS. Despite the multiple
attempts at reusing the existing gre_bridge logic, it seems
like linux bridge and ovs interfere with one another when used
at the same time.

Furthermore n-net requires an extra tunnel that neutron does not,
therefore, keeping the tunnel logics separated seem the most sensible
course of action at this point, but we may want to revisit this in the
future.

Depends-on: I6b4e5b82958e6d29dd450f1c4c9513f6a9e5053a
Change-Id: Id8d16877f09a1128c10f5c52438f6b7726c01f8e

commit_message:
Add Neutron DVR aiopcpu support

Configure the subnode to run the extra services required
for Neutron DVR, like the L3 agent (in 'dvr' mode).

The data path between the controller and the subnode is
established via a tunnel created using OVS. The collective
troubleshooting effort [1] confirmed that n-net can work
successfully with gre tunnels being setup with ovs, therefore
only one logic is going to be maintained.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171714/12

Depends-on: I6b4e5b82958e6d29dd450f1c4c9513f6a9e5053a
Change-Id: Id8d16877f09a1128c10f5c52438f6b7726c01f8e

commit_message:
Sort jobs in JobsView based on created_at value

Originally the jobs were displayed in the jobs table in the
order that they were returned by the API. This patch adds a line
to sort the list of jobs by their created_at attribute to make the
ordering of the table less arbitrary.

Change-Id: I45ed2365f8a47c34b6fcc81e1a919069aca663f8
Closes-Bug: 1441731

[{'created': '2015-04-07 17:24:22.000000000', 'message': 'Redundant events on group grant revocation

Revoke a project scoped token

You see 3 entries in revocation_event table

1) (id, user_id, project_id, role_id, issued_before)
2) (id, user_id,, issued_before)
3) (id, user_id,, issued_before)

2 & 3 are redundant. Definitely 3) is redundant as it is same as 2)

Both 2 & 3 are the result of handling notification fired by
_emit_invalidate_token_persistence.

Change-Id: I7199bcb9f9425004985e9db0833ce1f8a0ff5ac6
Closes-Bug: 1430951
'}]
commit_message:
Redundant events on group grant revocation

Revoke a project scoped token

You see 3 entries in revocation_event table

1) (id, user_id, project_id, role_id, issued_before)
2) (id, user_id,, issued_before)
3) (id, user_id,, issued_before)

2 & 3 are redundant. Definitely 3) is redundant as it is same as 2)

Both 2 & 3 are the result of handling notification fired by
_emit_invalidate_token_persistence.

Change-Id: I7199bcb9f9425004985e9db0833ce1f8a0ff5ac6
Closes-Bug: 1430951

commit_message:
Fixing Radware LBaaS v2 driver entity deletion

Fixing driver entity deletion bug
where driver mixin successful_completion function was not called properly
and left the entity not deleted in DB

Change-Id: Ifb25adea9da7921a0d2d414ef73ad403dc89a9ac
Closes-Bug: 1443060

commit_message:
Fix intermittent ipset_manager test failure

Change ipset_manager _refresh_set() to make a copy of the list of
IPs when creating a set, instead of using a reference, else any
change to the set could update the caller's data.

Also made the IpsetManagerTestCase classes always pass maxelem and
hashsize to the parent class.

Change-Id: I45fc716ab0952b80363b0c7dabae29cda05604dc
Closes-bug: #1442377

commit_message:
Enable ARP spoofing prevention by default

Turn on the ARP spoofing prevention added in
I7c079b779245a0af6bc793564fa8a560e4226afe by
default. It was disabled by default since it
was going into Kilo at the last minute and we
didn't want to risk shipping with a default
that might have broken an edge case that we
didn't consider.

This patch enables it by default since there
shouldn't be any need to have it disabled.

Change-Id: Id17939914ebf8292dce76ccb7d0f6486c91f49e5

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-31 09:20:12.000000000', 'message': 'Check if device name is valid when adding to the ring

Curently device names can be empty or start and/or end with spaces.
This can create unexpected results, for example these three commands

commit_message:
Check if device name is valid when adding to the ring

Currently device names can be empty or start and/or end with spaces.
This can create unexpected results, for example these three commands
are all valid:

swift-ring-builder account.builder add "r1z1-127.0.0.1:6000/" 1
swift-ring-builder account.builder add "r1z1-127.0.0.1:6000/sda " 1
swift-ring-builder account.builder add "r1z1-127.0.0.1:6000/ meta" 1

This patch validates device names and prevents empty names or names
starting and/or ending with spaces.

Also fixed the test "test_warn_at_risk" - the test passed if the
exception was not raised.

Closes-Bug: 1438579

Change-Id: I811b0eae7db503279e6429d985275bbab8b29c9f

commit_message:
Fix generating a CSR with an encrypted private key

If there is no passphrase, None should be passed to load_privatekey().

Change-Id: I2544c02f27341720fd87cf3a69c1b7c0c571bb8a

commit_message:
Fix expectations of order certificate test cases

Remove the checks that looked for generated_csr and plugin_name
meta values in a get order response.  These are field are for
use only internally to Barbican and are not return on a get
order request.

Change-Id: I5797eab13a1e33e95910d810f9e9b250e0fa3767
Closes-bug: #1443007

commit_message:
VMware: Fix volume relocate during detach

During volume detach, volume's shadow VM might need to be
relocated if storage DRS moved the Nova instance along with
volume's vmdk. The shadow VM is relocated to the current
datastore of instance and it's virtual disk is updated. For
relocate, we are not setting the destination host and it
defaults to source host. This can result in relocate failure
if this host cannot access the destination datastore. This
patch sets the destination host correctly to that of instance.

Change-Id: If51bbef6e2ca811e2fffdca906645cc963c27a3e
Closes-Bug: #1425486

[{'created': '2015-04-02 06:20:12.000000000', 'message': 'Merge flavor_extraspecs functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges flavor_extraspecs functional tests.

Change-Id: Iab41188b8e511a1a41dabee8bad48fd18cbd2b06

Merge flavor_extraspecs functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges flavor_extraspecs functional tests.

Change-Id: Iab41188b8e511a1a41dabee8bad48fd18cbd2b06

commit_message:
Merge flavor_manage functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges flavor_manage functional tests.

This commit also tags FlavorManageSampleJsonTests as ADMIN_API to avoid
AuthenticationException when create a test flavor

Change-Id: I5fe68870285cfee2b3254184209a7111b24f7223

commit_message:
WebSSO should use remote_id_attribute by protocol

WebSSO always use the remote_id_attribute from the
[federation] group. Fix the issue, by consuming the
protocol specific remote_id_attribute if available.

Change-Id: Icdc693965ec53e5ff8f1901af26c9232a20aef7e
Closes-Bug: #1441827

on microversions mechanism, clients can sent always a request without specifying microversion.
because http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/kilo/implemented/api-microversions.html#client-interaction contains

 If X-OpenStack-Nova-API-Version is not provided, act as if min_version was sent.

On IRC talking with John, I know he got an interesting idea.

A big concern about v2.1 API is strong validation, especially it denies unexpected properties with additionalProperties feature.
For big public cloud envs which need to receive requests from many kinds of client, additionalProperties feature is too strong and it might break some clients.
To avoid that, there is an idea for disabling additionalProperties feature when clients don't specify a microversion in a request.
That means additionalProperties feature doesn't work against the existing clients.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173243 is that.

If we can implement it, it is the same between v2 and v2.1 from client POV.
and John prefer "" as v2.1 min_version for the consistency.

I much prefer this idea, but I don't think "" is right on current situation.
The idea will be implemented in Liberty, and it is impossible to backport it to Kilo because of current stable branch policy.
And I feel we need an option for switching the default behavior because strong validation is exactly right and it should be default setting.
So I feel the min microversion "2.1" is right at this time.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-14 10:39:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

OK, so my mistake here, I think we can use the v2.0 entry to say if requests without a version are accepted.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-04-14 11:13:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-04-14 11:53:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14920, 'date': '2015-04-14 16:15:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 22:17:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-14 22:17:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

commit_message:
Add min/max of API microversions to version API

As nova-spec api-microversions, versions API needs to expose minimum
and maximum microversions to version API, because clients need to
know available microversions through the API. That is very important
for the interoperability.
This patch adds these versions as the nova-spec mentioned.

Note:
  As v2(not v2.1) API change manner, we have added new extensions if
  changing API. However, this patch doesn't add a new extension even
  if adding new parameters "version" and "min_version" because version
  API is independent from both v2 and v2.1 APIs.

Closes-Bug: #1443375

Change-Id: Id464a07d624d0e228fe0aa66a04c8e51f292ba0c

commit_message:
Fixes replication controller deletion

KubernetesCluster method to delete RC was using incorrect
property and there was a typo in execution plan making it
fail on validation

Also renames destroy* methods to delete* methods to match
Kubernetes terms

Change-Id: I7f36d6634df529a4a9e89fb545e1f2ab6a2dac93
Closes-Bug: #1443857

commit_message:
Refactor the getting roles logic in _keystone_identity

The list_from_csv in swift.common.utils is used from the composite
auth token support and this method has been used in
_integral_keystone_identity. There is same logic in
_keystone_identity so the logic would be replaced with list_from_csv.

Change-Id: I3d72a34e6fc21fbe1d7331954695b1e3e1b67816

commit_message:
Support HTTP_X_SERVICE_IDENTITY_STATUS in keystoneauth

Keystone's auth_token now supports delay denial when
a service token is invalid. This change handles
the consequences for determining 401 vs 403 responses.

Related-Bug: #1422389

Change-Id: I90ba062e357cccea061c7101463b82b7c5e69293

[{'created': '2015-04-14 15:01:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3
Closes-Bug: 1411063
'}]
commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3
Closes-Bug: 1411063

commit_message:
Cache negotiated api microversion for this server

*** WIP ***

If we negotiate an API microversion in the ironiccclient, cache
this value so that we don't need to re-negotiate it again for the
next API call. By default, we're caching the version for 5 minutes.

Change-Id: I4338b937bea056b7c92b5776585563e73949b39d
Blueprint: api-microversions

@Samuel - you're absolutely right, unfortunately IPv6 is borked without this patch. The good news is that eventlet upstream does finally have a branch that has IPv6 support in it (after a couple years), but its a big patch and I don't suspect it will land in eventlet upstream in the near future. Will add a config option so only those users that are adamant on having IPv6 can weigh the side effects of the blocking dns calls."}, {'account_id': 8992, 'date': '2014-09-04 16:16:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

FYI - eventlet branch containing the ipv6 changes is located at https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/tree/bb-40-greendns-ipv6'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-09-04 18:32:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Allowing blocking DNS in the proxy is pretty awful. I'm assuming this is for the cname_lookup middleware, as that's the only place I can think of that we do DNS operations outside of initialization.

Assuming that's true, I think we'd need a config option for blocking DNS in cname_lookup, and if it's set, cname_lookup needs to use a threadpool to do its DNS operations. Otherwise, imagine that a DNS lookup takes 1 second because things are slow (and sometimes things really do get slow). That limits your proxy to at most 1 request per second, and that's downright sad. Not only that, your throughput will fall to near zero because the proxy isn't moving bytes while it's blocking in DNS.

Now, if you used a threadpool of size 25, your proxy could accept 25 requests per second (slightly less sad), and more importantly, the proxy could continue to service existing clients while those DNS operations are blocking worker threads, so the throughput would remain okay.

Without some mitigation of the effects of slow DNS, I just can't take this patch. Yes, right now things don't work with ipv6 in that they crash, but I think that being ridiculously slow also counts as not working."}, {'account_id': 8992, 'date': '2014-09-16 23:20:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 8992, 'date': '2014-09-16 23:24:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I haven't added a general config option yet in the swift/common/__init__.py file yet prior to setting the EVENTLET_NO_GREENDNS enablement. However, I'm not 100% sure on how to do that yet since we need to enable it /prior/ to importing swift.common module anywhere in order to successfully disable the dns.

Unfortunately, there are different config files for each service and its not clear which service is running at the point that the swift/common is imported so we can't fully tell which config file to read the option for. The config option may need to be pushed to the startup scripts to handle this scenario."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 01:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix getaddrinfo if dnspython is installed.

If dnspython is present in the environment then eventlet
monkeypatches socket.getaddrinfo() with an implementation
which doesn't work for IPv6.

An ImportError will be reported if eventlet is pre-imported
and the magic env var 'EVENTLET_NO_GREENDNS' is not being set
as 'yes' for IPv6, otherwise we will set the env var as 'yes'
to disable eventlet greendns for IPv6.

An env variable 'OS_ENABLE_IPV6' is used to enable IPv6.

To improve dns queries for cname_lookup middleware, a threadpool
is used when eventlet greendns implemenation has been disabled
to support IPv6.

This patch has also been applied to other Openstack projects
such as glance(795e004eac3f032217ff9cb0047f1976306fbb71)
in order to work around the same problem and is intended to
be used in the same way.

DocImpact

Co-authored-by: Billy Olsen<billy.olsen@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I743c156423aa3b8313e00e14d5f126ea77e2a8fb
Closes-Bug: #1361204

commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3

commit_message:
Clean up keystone provider methods and tests

This patch does some cleanup by:
 - Removing unused methods such as remove_warnings and auth_keystone and corresponding tests
 - Moved the retry test into openstack_spec.rb and updated it to correspond to the new syntax
 - Moved the class reset method into keystone_spec.rb since that is the only place it is used

commit_message:
Fix ipv6 support

There is issue with ipv6 where address has to be in brackets, this causes the
underlying ruby TCPSocket to fail. Net::HTTP.new will fail without brackets on
joining the ipv6 address with :port or passing brackets to TCPSocket. It was
found that if we use Net::HTTP.start with url.hostname the incriminated code
won't be hit.

Change-Id: If9b2b629b701c4a4c2794c3b4af584bcfc47fc2d
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652

os-brick should use oslo_log for logging

os-brick should use oslo_log for logging. We have
seen failure in few unit test details are in Bug.

> Why not just have the user unset the password parameter?

commit_message:
New option replace_password for keystone_user

Adds a new option replace_password, which defaults
to 'True' for all keystone_user objects, that
has the effect of enforcing the password of a given
keystone_user. If this is disabled, the user may change
his or her password at a later time and not be reset
by the keystone Puppet module.

Ported from CID: I4bd59f233273374545953f16c7843488148096d6

Change-Id: Ib61128556fed816916af944ed7576e916081da07
Closes-Bug: #1400798

commit_message:
Exposes bug on role assignments creation

It should be possible to add both inherited and
non-inherited role assignments for the same actor
and target with the same role.

However, this is not currently possible. This
patch exposes this bug.

Related-Bug: #1403539

Change-Id: I9ee82b490ca36e9b2d135ef9ead54a2a4c312657

commit_message:
Use cliff deferred help instead of homemade one

This change removes openstackclient homemade hack to defer help
printing in initialize_app and uses cliff (new) option to defer
help printing.

Change-Id: Ie3e94ec96254745bfef8c5ff5abc405facfe1bea
Related-Bug: #1316622

commit_message:
Add warning message if unknown version supplied

Print a warning message if an unknown api version is supplied.
An attempt will be made to run the command anyway.

Change-Id: Idec8e88fe9621f10ec4b7eecd90708fb3730f56f

commit_message:
Encode secret strings in config files

This enhancement to oslo.config allows secret strings to be
encoded so prying eyes do not see passwords.

This change also relies on an external entity to encode the string
in the config file.  In our case, this would be in Ansible.

Change-Id: I4b245420ec7bc0af1788aef817cc35e00e84a25d
Implements-Story: #74991774
Fixes-Bug: #1350401
(cherry picked from commit b04dfa39f55d78cc5fe6e467d58ac3e51285c154)

commit_message:
Make group on /var/log/nova OS specific

On Ubuntu the group defaults to adm on /var/log/nova, on RH systems it
should be nova. Make it OS specific so it doesn't get re-assigned.

Change-Id: I989fd7888b7d509ac766afdb1bac6d3876f69542
Closes-Bug: #1267573

commit_message:
IPv6 support for migration check.

This enables the use of the '::0' IPv6 address for the vncserver_listen
parameter.

    class { 'nova::compute::libvirt':
      vncserver_listen         => '::0',
      migration_support        => true,
    }

Change-Id: Iec69a82c6a7bbf1b0f7364e87e1e3e37a876be9a
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652

[{'created': '2015-01-26 21:30:04.000000000', 'message': 'Database: add slave_connection support

Nova is able to talk to a read-only database for some tables so it
improves the scalability of MySQL server and reduce the access to the
server in charge of writes.

More documentation: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Slave_usage

Change-Id: I1d44332acb381b11d90b63535d274f535be26d55
'}]
commit_message:
Database: add slave_connection support

Nova is able to talk to a read-only database for some tables so it
improves the scalability of MySQL server and reduce the access to the
server in charge of writes.

More documentation: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Slave_usage

Change-Id: I1d44332acb381b11d90b63535d274f535be26d55

commit_message:
Add optional network_api_class parameter to nova::network::neutron class

This allows for overriding the default Neutron network API class in Nova.

Change-Id: Ic2b1cce115720a4ac1208b38facbb82fdf273173

commit_message:
Add Nova Aggregate support

Bring nova aggregate and availability zones support into puppet-nova.

  - Handle nil values and 0 lengths (Aimon Bustardo)
  - Remove extraneous whitespace on aggregate-create (Aimon Bustardo)

Implements: blueprint aggregate-handling

Change-Id: I9125d573a6a3cf4d444300d3570c4ab394c4ecd8

commit_message:
Adds Neutron to Start/Stop Scripts

Previously, Neutron was not included in the start/stop scripts.
This patch reads the NETWORK_MANAGER value from openstack.env
to start/stop either nova or neutron networking.

Change-Id: I85b31396c2b816b89f33206443c3d60cb4b7914b

commit_message:
rpc_backend: simplify parameters

Since Icehouse, there is no need to specify the whole Python namespace
for the backends.
We can now use keywords like "rabbit", "qpid" or "zmq".

This patch maintains backward compatibility with previous default
parameters in case someone overrides it with the default parameter.

Source: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/rpc.py#L48-L55

Closes-bug: #1405656

Change-Id: I23d1331e047a99cac3f4939f83de190275ca1236

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-13 14:02:11.000000000', 'message': 'modular resource checking infrastructure

This provides the infrastructure for modular resource checking, as
well as an example implementation for keystone (which has uncovered
bugs with openstack client vs. keystone upgrade).

The infrastructure includes:

- the resource script dispatcher, including the ability to disable
  using it all together via config.

- resource_save / resource_get scripts for our grenadedb registry
  (wrapper on ini files, but abstracted so we could do something
  different in the future)

- keystone resource script. This currently contains a bunch of
  commented code because openstackclient 404s in GET /v2.0/user after
  upgrade, though there is nothing in logs to figure out why.

Change-Id: I8666a96a817cfc333e50eed3b9aeffa5ac4aeec6

commit_message:
modular resource checking infrastructure

This provides the infrastructure for modular resource checking, as
well as an example implementation for keystone.

The infrastructure includes:

- the resource script dispatcher, including the ability to disable
  using it all together via config.

- resource_save / resource_get scripts for our grenadedb registry
  (wrapper on ini files, but abstracted so we could do something
  different in the future)

- keystone resource script.

Change-Id: I8666a96a817cfc333e50eed3b9aeffa5ac4aeec6

'}, {'created': '2015-03-31 22:03:22.000000000', 'message': 'Updating database models to fix time stamp errors

* Updated DB models to use sqlalchemy models TimeStampMixIn from
  our own version as our version had a bug in created_at timestamp
  being the same for all created clusters.
* As part of sqlalchemy models TimeStampMixIn, updated_at is an
  optional field, therefore changes to table definition was
  required.
* Updated API to reflect optional fields (e.g. updated_at)
* Removed wrapper around responce bodies as current this
  implementation did not allow for filtering unuset fields.
* Added test to verify created_at times are different and in
  correct order.

commit_message:
Updating database models to fix time stamp errors

* Updated DB models to use sqlalchemy models TimeStampMixIn from
  our own version as our version had a bug in created_at timestamp
  being the same for all created clusters.
* As part of sqlalchemy models TimeStampMixIn, updated_at is an
  optional field, therefore changes to table definition was
  required.
* Updated API to reflect optional fields (e.g. updated_at)
* Added test to verify created_at, updated_at and deleted_at times
  are in correct order for corresponding changes (e.g. create,
  update and delete).

closes-bug: 1428896
Change-Id: I0047a197e48cbc017d7f750da797967108da423c

commit_message:
Do not export REG_HALT_UNREGISTER between hook scripts

Do not rely on environment changes (like exporting REG_HALT_UNREGISTER)
to persist between different hooks run. This helps when the hooks are
run in different new environments every time.

Instead, in 99-unregister redo the same checks on REG_METHOD as done in
00-rhel-registration, still respecting REG_HALT_UNREGISTER in case the
user does not want to unregister the image generated.

Change-Id: Id594dcd72334f38a2fa96da21206da77a83d7a1a
Closes-Bug: #1434431

commit_message:
Move _update_project_quota into a common Workflow ancestor

Both CreateProject and UpdateProject workflows use almost the same
method _update_project_quota which is not very good. Reduce the
duplication by introducing a common ancestor for these 2 workflow
classes.

Change-Id: I12a056cd3d3a8c8c67b3735f3337c1efbb4fd6f5

(1 comment)

I understand the concern that the doc is slightly misleading, in that there is no backwards compatibility w.r.t. services_roles, and I support making it clearer. But I don't like that the proposed change obscures the fact that service_roles without a prefix will apply to all account prefixes.

If the real goal is to *require* service_roles to always have a prefix then that must be achieved by a code change, not just removing from the doc."}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2015-03-23 15:13:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Comment in-line

Also, wrt:

> If the real goal is to *require* service_roles to always have a prefix then that must be achieved by a code change

If the goal is to require a prefix for service_roles, then I  disagree that this is more secure. As-is, the rules are  straightforward -- no-prefix applies to everything; an explicit prefix overrides this. Since serivce_roles introduces an *additional* requirement on the required roles, it's safer (more secure) to have the default to be that no-prefix applies. Otherwise, if you are adding a new reseller_profix and forgot to specify the prefix, you be less secure since the new reseller_prefix won't require x-service-token."}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-03-24 10:11:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your review.

About the real goal, I think we better to *require* a prefix for a service_roles.
The rule "no-prefix applies to everything" is reasonable to keep backward compatibility but not good for general usage. (Without backward compatibility the case, adding a new reseller_prefix and forgot to specify the prefix, it's better to reject the request as not having appropriate roles)
And I was wondering if we support oslo.config. I think we need to create a key for retrieving dynamically because the key can be created using other keys and their values. The rough image of thelogic is the following. http://paste.openstack.org/show/195807/
So I think it is better to restrict flexible configuration setting step by step (in the future).

> If the real goal is to *require* service_roles to always have a prefix then that
>  must be achieved by a code change, not just removing from the doc.

My idea was the current logic "no-prefix applies to everything" is used only for backward compatibility in short term and then restrict flexible configuration
setting in the future and reduce users impact. Therefore I uploaded this patch to clarify the description.

> How about just dropping 'For backwards compatibility'
> Just drop "For backwards compatibility" -- it adds nothing to the description

To users I don't want to use this setting so I would like to keep "backward compatibility".

How about the following:
For backward compatibility, if either of these parameters is specified without a
prefix then it applies to all reseller_prefixes.'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-03-25 05:57:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-25 06:34:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Clarify the description of backward compatibility in Keystoneauth's docstring

If no prefix implies for the operator_roles and/or service_roles
parameters applies to all reseller_prefixes in the code.
But from backward comatibility point of view, the service_roles
parameter is newly introduced parameter so it is better to clarify
the docstring.

Change-Id: I8b0d5aeff785c21b8a8b0f5b20f774fad868016d

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Add Security Group Step Unit Tests

This patch adds unit tests for the security group step.  These tests are
focused around the controller and its related components (no selenium tests
or view tests).

Change-Id: I14dbc603e3bafdcebcb13b0ef7f77d05a26a2122

commit_message:
Removing unused variables in horizon angular

Before we can enable a global check for unused variables, we need to clean
up the code first. This way, the gate won't barf when we try to enable the
global unused and undef jshint config.

This patch addresses the files in angular horizon files.

Change-Id: I0495aa4d6a3dd16a3e6190e0187adf6069aa361a
Partially-Closes-bug: #1441794

commit_message:
Fix Terminate Instance on network topology page

It failed because not all the info expected by the
`project.instances.IndexView` was provided by network topology view
while rendering part of Instances table in an iframe.

Change-Id: If36f877517d454430320b90362fd0d5207dbf9df
Closes-Bug: #1398468
(cherry picked from commit a1416b6d1dbb084eeca1b489f77983449c7a5ed4)

commit_message:
Fix incorrect ca arguments for calling ceilometer client

With ceilometer configured with SSL, Horizon fail to connect to
ceilometer to load the meters(usage data) due to it passed a wrong
of ca argument for ceilometer client. Should use 'cacert' instead
of 'ca_file'.

See ceilometer client:
https://github.com/openstack/python-ceilometerclient/blob/master/ceilometerclient/v2/client.py#L53

Change-Id: I296c61119e07cd2e19079ef62054c5837fa13114
Closes-Bug: #1388764
(cherry picked from commit 8164075f5b6b24972503c9d27f78e0228dce9716)

commit_message:
rpc: Allow to configure the rabbitmq heartbeat

For testing we can need to disable or change the rate of the heartbeat
Currently we have to set the value manually in each componments or
to write multiple [[post-config|$<APP>_CONF]] section in local.conf.

This change will allow to configure all componments at once with only two
lines.

Also, we don't set default values to continue to use oslo.messaging
defaults.

Change-Id: Ieaca60ca1cd6d7455b66ce490a9b023df431e9c3

commit_message:
Add RST Glossary

Automatically convert the glossary from DocBook XML to RST with each
build and use it for building the RST guides.

Add the glossary to User Guides and Networking Guide.

Use glossary in User Guides in places where it was used before. This
removes one TODO.

Fix CORS capitalization.

Partial-Bug: #1421813
Change-Id: I3fba6d54b01759f39f8e1467a7606cdbd2dd0165

When a cluster is deployed, it's DNS settings contain only external
servers. It makes impossible to access intranet resources from
cluster nodes.

- replase DNS list for cluster with admin node IP (only if dns_list
was not customized from a test case)

- in 'revert_snapshot', place sync_time() before access to nailgun

Change-Id: Idf3621a94ae109d93a9235c83c08d8fb2d792826
Closes-Bug: #1442675
"}]
commit_message:
Use admin node as DNS in system tests

When a cluster is deployed, it's DNS settings contain only external
servers. It makes impossible to access intranet resources from
cluster nodes.

- replase DNS list for cluster with admin node IP (only if dns_list
was not customized from a test case)

- in 'revert_snapshot', place sync_time() before access to nailgun

Change-Id: Idf3621a94ae109d93a9235c83c08d8fb2d792826
Closes-Bug: #1442675

commit_message:
Ignore *.img images in files folder

Some (qcow) images have .img file name extension (e.g. Cirros).
Ignore such files in files/ folder too (as we already do
with .qcow2 and .gz images).

Change-Id: Iac8593b65205e25fd3f94244a136c584d9af8eab

commit_message:
Fix the incorrect work of method _removeApplicationEndpoints()

Fixed typo in method implementation. `select` command was used
for data filtration instead of `where` 

Change-Id: I80b859333089865f8f054b3cf35746e65eeef192
Closes-Bug: #1443686

commit_message:
context: reuse base oslo.context class for to_dict()

It is need to conform to expectations of consumers that rely on
oslo.context behaviour (f.e. oslo.log that relies [1] on user_identity
field being set for context objects).

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.log/blob/master/oslo_log/_options.py#L99

Closes-Bug: #1433687
Change-Id: I95e803b96e6e3e5b8c12298dc6327b974330c639

urls. This means that 'openstack user list' will not function after

"}]
commit_message:
fix juno upgrade-keystone script

The following fixes the upgrade-keystone script for juno. There was a
copy/paste error in the original version of this script, which we
landed, which sets the version discovery of admin urls to public
urls. This means that 'openstack user list' will not function after
this upgrade.

Nothing currently tests this in our stack, which is how this got
through. The attempt to add keystone resource scripts in module
grenade exposed it.

Change-Id: I08d0a2992d0cf28756fb7d08aef6b67b0e597748

commit_message:
cleanup and document where we stand

This is a smorgasbord cleanup patch which does the following:

- moves all the inline function definitions in grenade.sh out to
  either bootstrap or upgrade libraries.

- gets rid of grenaderc.settings, this is handled by modular shutdown
  / upgrade service checking.

- consolidates all settings into grenaderc

- removes all variables that were extraneous, and came from very very
  early history of grenade.

- Documents the current flow and assumptions in grenade.sh as much as
  possible.

Change-Id: I3d2fa30240247690e3f45dcb0be93672808914f6

I've worked with folks in the Mistral team a little over the past year (not as much as I would have liked, due only to lack of time on my part), and they've always felt like a part of the OpenStack community. IMHO they pass the "one of us" test.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-04-03 10:22:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The main issue/risk with Mistral is the bus factor (with two developers accounting for 2/3 of the Kilo commits and reviews). But I think that's more adequately described using a tag (team:bus-factor ?) to communicate the (current) inherent fragility of the project to the rest of the world, rather than clipping its wings forever by keeping it out of the tent.

[1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_factor"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-04-03 16:00:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I am personally not such a fan of the bus factor; have you looked at how many of the global requirements that we have are also at risk of the bus factor. You might be somewhat astonished...

Not to pick on anyone dependency but here are a few...

* https://github.com/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/graphs/contributors (michal bayer is in the 90+ percentage of all the commits)

* netifaces (also mostly one guy)

* six (also mostly one guy)

* ...

IMHO we need to stop being dishonest to ourselves and just understand that this is how the real world works; where not all projects are backed by X companies or Y people (innovation doesn't always work like that...) and just figure out how to deal with our own anxieties first (because others have figured out how to deal with theirs and still use these libraries...)"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-04-03 17:16:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Note that if we have diversity that's great, but we need to accept the real world and understand that's now always how this goes (and doesn't seem to actual be the common case of how it works out; at least in relation to libraries)..."}, {'account_id': 9432, 'date': '2015-04-03 17:33:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

While we can't address the bus factor completely, some commentary: 1) it's been a stable team of 4 over last year 2) StackStorm is committed to supporting it. Yes we are a small company and this is a risk, too... that leads to 3) catch-22: folks from Huawei, HP, Rackspace and Symantec are looking to contribute but reluctant, in part due to uncertainty of the project status. Moving Mistral into the space may help break the vicious cycle.

@Joshua: re using taskflow: Renat have made a big step towards potential taskflow integration, refactoring to pluggable workflow engine and handler, with two workflow types already implemented. Still work on both sides but some progress toward. 

@Zane, thanks, your contribution with ideas and vision has been very valuable."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-04-03 18:55:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Dmitri sounds great; u know where to find me :-P'}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2015-04-04 04:25:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-02 18:02:22.000000000', 'message': 'Adding Mistral Workflow Service to OpenStack

Provide a simple YAML-based language to write workflows  (tasks and
transitions), and a service that allows to upload them, modify, run them at at
scale and in a highly available manner, manage and monitor workflow executions
and states of individual tasks.

The code base has existed for 1 year and 4 months in the stackforge code
namespace.

Mistral community has been consistently growing from cycle to cycle and now
includes more than 10 contributors from Mirantis, StackStorm, Huawei, HP,
Symantec, and Ericsson.

We will hold elections for our PTL, currently Renat Akhmerov, on a regular basis
according to standard OpenStack community practices. We hold weekly team
meetings on IRC where we discuss Mistral design, blueprints, issues, roadblocks
and roadmap. We also use openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org mailing list for all
offline discussions related to new ideas, design and implementation. Blueprints
and bugs are tracked using Launchpad according to OpenStack rules. The gerrit
review board rules are strictly followed. Mistral is integrated with devstack,
and runs tempus functional tests as gate tests. Functional tests are integrated
with devstack, tempest, and rally and run as gates.

Mistral is implemented using libraries and technologies adopted by OpenStack
community such as SqlAlchemy for object persistence, oslo.messaging for RPC
communications, and others.

Mistral is also integrated with other OpenStack services. It has full dynamic
support for OpenStack actions - Keystone, Nova, Glance, Heat, Cinder, Neutron,
so any openstack operations can be used in workflows. Murano project has the
ability to call Mistral workflows from Murano PL. There are also two patches on
review that add Mistral related resources into Heat (workflows and cron
triggers). There is interest from other projects to using Mistral, expressed
from Congress, Trove, Solum, Barbican, Heat, and Keystone.

Change-Id: I5d0e877903c3f55ce2330e301b27da9435f677c5

commit_message:
Adding Mistral Workflow Service to OpenStack

Provide a simple YAML-based language to write workflows  (tasks and
transitions), and a service that allows to upload them, modify, run them at at
scale and in a highly available manner, manage and monitor workflow executions
and states of individual tasks.

The code base has existed for 1 year and 4 months in the stackforge code
namespace.

Mistral community has been consistently growing from cycle to cycle and now
includes more than 10 contributors from Mirantis, StackStorm, Huawei, HP,
Symantec, and Ericsson.

We will hold elections for our PTL, currently Renat Akhmerov, on a regular basis
according to standard OpenStack community practices. We hold weekly team
meetings on IRC where we discuss Mistral design, blueprints, issues, roadblocks
and roadmap. We also use openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org mailing list for all
offline discussions related to new ideas, design and implementation. Blueprints
and bugs are tracked using Launchpad according to OpenStack rules. The gerrit
review board rules are strictly followed. Mistral is integrated with devstack,
and runs tempus functional tests as gate tests. Functional tests are integrated
with devstack, tempest, and rally and run as gates.

Mistral is implemented using libraries and technologies adopted by OpenStack
community such as SqlAlchemy for object persistence, oslo.messaging for RPC
communications, and others.

Mistral is also integrated with other OpenStack services. It has full dynamic
support for OpenStack actions - Keystone, Nova, Glance, Heat, Cinder, Neutron,
so any openstack operations can be used in workflows. Murano project has the
ability to call Mistral workflows from Murano PL. There are also two patches on
review that add Mistral related resources into Heat (workflows and cron
triggers). There is interest from other projects to using Mistral, expressed
from Congress, Trove, Solum, Barbican, Heat, and Keystone.

Change-Id: I5d0e877903c3f55ce2330e301b27da9435f677c5

commit_message:
consolidate all target setup into prep-target

There were a remarkable number of scripts that we ran during the
target setup phase, that all boiled down to very small
activities.

 - upgrade-devstack - copied 1 file
 - upgrade-infra - cloned gr
 - upgrade-oslo - actually *did nothing* (now that we install
   libraries from pypi)

Consolidating them all into a unified prep-target makes understanding
what's happening on the target setup simpler.

Change-Id: I0a1a41714fd9749857ccfc0825414f331f44ec2a

commit_message:
module upgrade service tests

Move the logic of check-sanity, which looks for services that should
be started and logs that should exist, into the per service upgrade
scripts.

Change-Id: I3e5a90a3d2c47b8224a7e7ce3a45a19837872252

commit_message:
Add app name|uuid argument to "solum app logs"

The app logs command was listing every log for
every app; this patch adds an app argument to
filter by app.

Change-Id: Ia5429bd7680df8f5832c68eca1057db7ffe75a55
Closes-Bug: #1444043

commit_message:
Enable alternate error message for OpenSSL 1.0.2

Since OpenSSL will no longer handle unsigned CSRs, this fix enabled
accepting the error message we now get from the API. While retaining
backwards compatibility with the functionality on OpenSSL 1.0.1.

Change-Id: Icae9b6aebe7d3ec4c788185e1b11e5c8f52d4caf
Related-Bug: #1443075

commit_message:
Sign CSRs issued in SnakeOilCA tests

In OpenSSL 1.0.2a CSRs that are not signed are now considered invalid
and will throw an error when trying to load them. This commit fixes that
and also moves the repeated code to a single function to improve the
tests' readability.

Change-Id: I7a60717b7f473a6f2724eed515aa094819b7f621
Closes-Bug: #1443075

commit_message:
Filter session-XXX.scope files from logs

There are 1000's of these being archived individually, adding
about 5 minutes to the fedora jobs, taking up inodes on the
logs server and increasing the size of the console log.
If we want the contents we can check the journal file.

Change-Id: Ia93fe51be457ab058d4d3b355f803a1075f352da

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-09 09:04:21.000000000', 'message': "Create rule in a policy via Horizon

Add form to Policy Details page that lets user create a new rule in the policy.

* congress.py: Rename SERVICE_TABLE_SEPARATOR to more general TABLE_SEPARATOR.
  New API functions to create rule and more ways to get data source's schema.

datasources/
* utils.py: Data source related helper functions.
* views.py: Rename constant.

policies/
* urls.py: New url for rule creation form.
* views.py: Generate lists of all data source tables and columns and add them
  to the template context.

policies/rules/
* tables.py: New button to show rule creation form.
* views.py: New view for rule creation form.
* workflows.py: Steps in rule creation form. Translate user inputs into
  Datalog and send off to the Congress server.

policies/templates/policies/
* detail.html: Change to extend new base file, which includes new static files.
  Store lists of data source tables and columns here for use by child
  templates.

policies/templates/policies/rules/
* _create_conditions.html: Rule creation step where user defines head column
  mapping, join, and negation conditions.
* _create_output.html: Rule creation step where user defines rule metadata plus
  policy table name and columns.
* _mapping_row.html: Template for a row of inputs that defines a head column
  mapping.
* create.html: Rule creation modal window.

static/admin/css/
* policies.css: Custom CSS used in Policies panel.

static/admin/js/
* policies.js: Custom JavaScript used in Policies panel.

templates/admin/
* _scripts.html: Custom JavaScript files used in Admin dashboard.
* base.html: Custom CSS and JavaScript files used in Admin dashboard.

Includes partial implementation of table aliases for self-joins. Does not
include: devstack support to copy over new files and handle new static files,
usage of builtin tables, data preview before submitting rule, policy table name
and column autocompletion in Output step, redisplay of rule creation form upon
failure to create rule, robust input validation.

Partially Implements: blueprint horizon-create-policies

Change-Id: I6ef7e15c34d639f5eb09303077893dbf289347f9
