commit_message:
Create rule in a policy via Horizon

Add form to Policy Details page that lets user create a new rule in the policy.
Update Horizon setup in devstack installation script to install JavaScript and
CSS files used in Policies panel.

* congress.py: Rename SERVICE_TABLE_SEPARATOR to more general TABLE_SEPARATOR.
  New API functions to create rule and more ways to get data source's schema.

datasources/
* utils.py: Data source related helper functions.
* views.py: Rename constant.

policies/
* urls.py: New url for rule creation form.
* views.py: Generate lists of all data source tables and columns and add them
  to the template context.

policies/rules/
* tables.py: New button to show rule creation form.
* views.py: New view for rule creation form.
* workflows.py: Steps in rule creation form. Translate user inputs into
  Datalog and send off to the Congress server.

policies/templates/policies/
* detail.html: Change to extend new base file, which includes new static files.
  Store lists of data source tables and columns here for use by child
  templates.

policies/templates/policies/rules/
* _create_conditions.html: Rule creation step where user defines head column
  mapping, join, and negation conditions.
* _create_output.html: Rule creation step where user defines rule metadata plus
  policy table name and columns.
* _mapping_row.html: Template for a row of inputs that defines a head column
  mapping.
* create.html: Rule creation modal window.

static/admin/css/
* policies.css: Custom CSS used in Policies panel.

static/admin/js/
* policies.js: Custom JavaScript used in Policies panel.

templates/admin/
* _scripts.html: Custom JavaScript files used in Admin dashboard.
* base.html: Custom CSS and JavaScript files used in Admin dashboard.

Includes partial implementation of table aliases for self-joins. Does not
include: usage of builtin tables, data preview before submitting rule, policy
table name and column autocompletion in Output step, redisplay of rule creation
form upon failure to create rule, robust input validation.

Partially Implements: blueprint horizon-create-policies

Change-Id: I6ef7e15c34d639f5eb09303077893dbf289347f9

commit_message:
The first functional test

Just implementing a single functional test to start things off.

This test introduces a new test dependency on os-client-config.
os-client-config is used to configure the SDK to run its functional test
on a particular cloud.

To run the functional tests do a

    tox -e functional

Unit tests continue to be run the same way as always.

Change-Id: Id1e8233c5e366e6ec864fb435f7f3cbf290ffae0

commit_message:
Add swift-ec-info tool

This tool is for inspecting and doing validation from a single
object on disk.
WIP on the unit tests

Usage: swift-ec-info [options] OBJECT_FILE

Options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  -P POLICY_NAME, --policy-name=POLICY_NAME
                        Specify storage policy name

Examples:

swift-ec-info /path/to/ecchunk -P ec21
Policy:
ECStoragePolicy(0, 'ec21', is_default=True, is_deprecated=False, policy_type='erasure_coding'), EC config(ec_type=jerasure_rs_vand, ec_segment_size=1048576, ec_ndata=2, ec_nparity=1)

Erasure Coding Metadata:
Encoding Fragment Archive Index: 2
Encoding Segment Size: 1048576
Encoding Scheme: jerasure_rs_vand 2+1

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ief288e46ef974d9c5e60ce45d8ef68c9ad34d061

nodes(data nodes) and then do the decoding. This may fail the read if

This patch adds one EC policy config: ec_read_all(default to false).
If it's true, proxy will try to read from all the nodes(data + parity)
and do the decoding. This will benefit setup with some old buggy disks.
However the read response time may increase.

commit_message:
EC: Allow proxy to read from all SN in EC policy

Currently when decoding proxy would only fetch data from the first k
nodes(data nodes) and then do the decoding. This may fail the read if
there's some failure happen
This patch adds one EC policy config: ec_read_all(default to false).
If it's true, proxy will try to read from all the nodes(data + parity)
and do the decoding. This will benefit setup with some old buggy disks.
However the read response time may increase.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Iba3a39314f23322f7adb2571ed049b135fbacabc
Signed-off-by: Yuan Zhou <yuan.zhou@intel.com>

Hmm, ok, I wrote a script that will throw test data and compare the results of grabbing the same ranges from the same file but stored in an EC and REPL containers.

It works, but there is a difference when we request the last byte (so a bounds edge test).

    matt@ec-saio2:~$ curl -i -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/cont_ec/obj -X GET -r 2060-2070,4131-4141
  HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
  Content-Length: 291
  Last-Modified: Wed, 01 Apr 2015 22:51:50 GMT
  Connection: close
  Etag: 8e909f86393c4fc052da4a8eddaa3bd7
  X-Timestamp: 1427928709.92318
  Date: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 02:25:16 GMT
  Content-Type: multipart/byteranges;boundary=8bf9cfa89d4cfcf5b740198acdfd3ba8
  X-Trans-Id: txc1ea520ef1c846888f2fd-00551ca88c

  --8bf9cfa89d4cfcf5b740198acdfd3ba8
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 2060-2070/4141

  NABLE=.*$/R
  --8bf9cfa89d4cfcf5b740198acdfd3ba8
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 4131-4141/4141

  fi
  exit 0

  --8bf9cfa89d4cfcf5b740198acdfd3ba8--matt@ec-saio2:~$ curl -i -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/cont_repl/obj -X GET -r 2060-2070,4131-4141
  HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
  Content-Length: 291
  Accept-Ranges: bytes
  Last-Modified: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 00:28:34 GMT
  Etag: 8e909f86393c4fc052da4a8eddaa3bd7
  X-Timestamp: 1427934513.60803
  Content-Type: multipart/byteranges;boundary=b2e2aeee23c645d7a7637978d1fe92d  0
  X-Trans-Id: txc3584b40971146c195101-00551ca895
  Date: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 02:25:25 GMT

  --b2e2aeee23c645d7a7637978d1fe92d0
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 2060-2070/4141

  NABLE=.*$/R
  --b2e2aeee23c645d7a7637978d1fe92d0
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 4131-4140/4141

  fi
  exit 0

The output data is the same, its the Content-Ranges get reported back differently. Replication, if you request larger then the file size returns: 

  'x-(<size>-1)/<size>'

E.g:

    4131-4140/4141

Whereas EC specifies:

  'x-<upper_range_supplied>/<size>'

E.g:

  bytes 4131-4141/4141

Although this might be better demonstrated by another failed bounds check:

   matt@ec-saio2:~$ curl -i -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/cont_ec/obj -X GET -r 1030-1040,2066-2076,3101-3111,4136-4146
  HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
  Content-Length: 542
  Last-Modified: Wed, 01 Apr 2015 22:51:50 GMT
  Connection: close
  Etag: 8e909f86393c4fc052da4a8eddaa3bd7
  X-Timestamp: 1427928709.92318
  Date: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 02:39:29 GMT
  Content-Type: multipart/byteranges;boundary=75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef
  X-Trans-Id: txcd24e02e5caf446a999e2-00551cabe1

  --75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 1030-1040/4141

  {USER}:${US
  --75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 2066-2076/4141

  .*$/RSYNC_E
  --75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 3101-3111/4141

  in director
  --75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 4136-4146/4141

  it 0

  --75897e307284549529c97e5512f0edef--
  matt@ec-saio2:~$ curl -i -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/cont_repl/obj -X GET -r 1030-1040,2066-2076,3101-3111,4136-4146
  HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
  Content-Length: 542
  Accept-Ranges: bytes
  Last-Modified: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 00:28:34 GMT
  Etag: 8e909f86393c4fc052da4a8eddaa3bd7
  X-Timestamp: 1427934513.60803
  Content-Type: multipart/byteranges;boundary=0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb
  X-Trans-Id: tx2c2a4bea5fc34f4aa2c1a-00551cabed
  Date: Thu, 02 Apr 2015 02:39:41 GMT

  --0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 1030-1040/4141

  {USER}:${US
  --0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 2066-2076/4141

  .*$/RSYNC_E
  --0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 3101-3111/4141

  in director
  --0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb
  Content-Type: application/octet-stream
  Content-Range: bytes 4136-4140/4141

  it 0

  --0207a7f4bd79ea65fd827555084cfefb--

Where here EC again does:

  x-<upper-bound-supplied>/<size>
  4136-4146/4141

And REPL:

  'x-(<size>-1)/<size>'
  4136-4140/4141

It isn't really broken in the sense the same bytes comes back, but they both (EC and REPL) don't behave the same.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-04-02 03:19:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-02 04:06:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified+1

@Sam, I made some tests and it all passed. Looks good! After that I looked at the code and found using a deprecated package so put -1. But I continue to review with the current code.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-04-09 00:25:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Yeah, unfortunately rfc822 really is the best tool here.

If I have a file pointer "fp" containing a single-part MIME message, I can type this:

    m = rfc822.Message(fp, 0)

and what happens is (a) `m` is an rfc822.Message object with the MIME headers in it, and (b) fp is now at the beginning of the document body.

I tried rewriting it with email.parser, so this:

    ep = email.parser.Parser()
    m = ep.parse(fp, headersonly=True)

What happens is that (a) m is an email.Message object with the MIME headers in it, and (b) fp is at EOF. The document body has been slurped into memory (which is JUST EFFING MARVELOUS for big objects) and then thrown away.

It goes without saying that this behavior is not particularly helpful.

I will admit that I copied the existing use of rfc822.Message from formpost.py without really thinking about it, but the exercise of trying to use email.parser.Parser instead has really shown me the value of not using email.parser.Parser. It's easy to switch between the two when you have the whole message in memory, but as soon as you have to start streaming, email.parser becomes pretty much useless.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-04-09 00:25:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-09 01:16:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Verified+1

This commit lets clients receive multipart/byteranges responses (see
RFC 7232, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

resuming now works on multipart/byteranges responses. Before, it only
worked on 200 responses or 206 responses for a single byte
range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

RFC 7232, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

GetOrHeadHandler got a base class extracted from it that treats an
HTTP response as a sequence of byte-range responses. This way, it can
continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

commit_message:
EC: support multiple ranges for GET requests

This commit lets clients receive multipart/byteranges responses (see
RFC 7232, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

GetOrHeadHandler got a base class extracted from it that treats an
HTTP response as a sequence of byte-range responses. This way, it can
continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

There are a couple of bonus fixes in here, too. For starters, download
resuming now works on multipart/byteranges responses. Before, it only
worked on 200 responses or 206 responses for a single byte
range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

Also, the MIME response for replicated objects got tightened up a
little. Before, it had some leading and trailing CRLFs which, while
allowed by RFC 7232, provide no benefit. Now, both replicated and EC
multipart/byteranges avoid extraneous bytes. This let me re-use the
Content-Length calculation in swob instead of having to hack around
it.

Change-Id: I16fc65e0ec4e356706d327bdb02a3741e36330a0

commit_message:
Validation of duplicate segmentation ID

The patch set fixes the problem described in the launchpad
bug 1443387 where the L2 gateway service plugin was not
checking whether the segmentation ID specified in the
l2-gateway-connection-create operation is already present in the
interface's VXLAN-to-VLAN binding.

Closes-Bug: 1443387
Change-Id: I42a170c479600ce0f45ba3620e665562b6af9b98

commit_message:
Cap paramiko on stable/icehouse

When requirements were capped on stable/icehouse, paramiko was left out.

This caps paramiko at 1.15.2 which is the latest release being used in
the current stable/icehouse check runs.

Change-Id: Ibcfff1eb0f080c1797365449eba3d406e46ddb41

commit_message:
Add timeout for keystoneclient session

Currently, we only apply timeout on ceilometer api, but not on keystone
api as well, this is not consistent. Keystone api may be slow, or worse,
stuck, then ceilometerclient will not return timely. This issue has caused
availability problem in our environment when ceilometer alarm service
has been running for a long time.

Change-Id: I0d5f82ff9cf4132a1de2f0b649908483326e116e
Closes-Bug: #1436249

commit_message:
Add support for having comments in the exclude file

This commit adds the support to have comments in the exclude file.
After this commit anything after a '#' will be treated as a comment
and ignored for matching. A new option --print-exclude is added which
will print out what is being skipped by the exclude file with any
comments in the file.

Change-Id: Ia357730f918e0a57cf2ac51cd8195e2721667511

@Elena, the sync seems to be correct. Some relevant questions:

1. do you envision this bug is fixed in kilo, or in liberty only? If just Liberty, then I would be glad to postpone the sync till that time.

2. It seems that we don't use ProcessLauncher in case of single worker [1]. So in that case it would mean that SIGHUP handling would not work in some configurations. Is it correct? I think we should not allow such a significant difference in behaviour in the tree.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/wsgi.py#L229

Hi, @Ihar!

1. I'd prefer to fix it in Kilo, but if the patches won't be able to make it in Kilo I'd certainly have to postpone (and, perhaps, consider a backport).

2. You are right, in case when the number of workers is 0, common.service code is not used at all. I am going to research the reason why it was done that way and whether we can use ServiceLauncher (which also supports handling of SIGHUPs) instead.
   For now, I think that adding SIGHUP support for multiple worker mode in neutron-server as well as for other neutron services that use common.service code (dhcp agent, l3-agent, metadata agent) may be considered as a first step.

@Elena, as I said, I'm concerned that we will introduce a feature that is not supported in single worker case (the default till Kilo). commit_message:
Sync service from oslo-incubator

This sync includes changes that are required to fix handling
of SIGHUP in Neutron.

The following changes and bugfixes are included:

d24b658 Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher"
593005b ProcessLauncher: reload config file in parent process on SIGHUP
f29e865 Store ProcessLauncher signal handlers on class level
bf92010 Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher

Change-Id: If0aab4e8978422346f6ba4c9e6272cdaf39db6cb
Closes-Bug: #1433142
Related-Bug: #1276694

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

This change will result in tons of exceptions in the server log now whenever the server is stopped for any period of time. Even if the clocks aren't out of sync, the agents will report state and the reports will build up in the queue when the server isn't running. Once the server starts, it will start to drain the queue and will raise Exceptions for every one of these even though it isn't really a problem.

That logic isn't really there to detect different clock times, it's just to skip processing stale updates from agents that built up while the server was not running. That's why it's compared against the start time."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-03-23 20:48:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-2

I actually faced this problem in my environment, where yes - it was a user error - that I had a clock miss match between the two nodes. The problem was, when i started the neutron agent on the compute, it would say "AMQP Connected" but then if I'd go do a "neutron agent-list" on the server, it wouldn't list the agent at all. Only when i enabled the debug logs on the neutron server, that I was able to decipher that it could be related to timestamps. 

Maru, I am ready to go for a dev mailing-list discussion. But just like what Kevin pointed out, it's just dumping an exception about what is the cause for the error for better detection and then improving a bit of the server logging. It doesn't attempt to solve the problem or do anything extra beyond what is being done today.'}, {'account_id': 14323, 'date': '2015-03-25 12:27:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Fine, it can bite a developer who misconfigures a multi-node setup, but that's not really the use case that we're trying to target. Hi Armando,
I didn't mean just the same thing. In this patch, I check for the agent time miss match for the first time start of the agent and that's when I was throwing the exception. Did you suggest that I have that check or just wanted me to re-write the current 'debug' log level to 'warning'? :)"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-13 06:26:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

I replied to the message on the list, but I will copy it here as well for reference: 

I would like to see some form of this merged at least as an error message. If a server has a bad CMOS battery and suffers a power outage, it's clock could easily be several years behind. In that scenario, the NTP daemon could refuse to sync due to a sanity check."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-13 06:36:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Maru, I understand your concern. I don't agree with trying to compensate for or auto-correct the clock diff. However, there is a pretty easy error for us to detect here that I think is worth warning about in the error log. It's very difficult to troubleshoot otherwise. 

As long as the exception is removed, it doesn't change how the data is actually processed so I don't think scope creep should be a major concern. We do calculations based on timestamps (for now), so I think it makes sense to at least warn people about time inputs occurring that make no sense."}, {'account_id': 9775, 'date': '2015-04-13 15:12:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 15894, 'date': '2015-04-13 15:12:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-18 18:08:14.000000000', 'message': "Improve error detection on agent registration

Neutron agents like the L2 openvswitch agent, gets connected to AMQP
once the service is started and the neutron-server node is reachable
from the neutron agent node. However, the neutron-server may reject
and return the request if there's a timestamp difference between the
two nodes. Currently there's no good way to detect this condition
esp from the agent node. This fix will improve the error detection
logic by throwing an exception back to the agent from the
neutron-server suggesting the cause of the error. It will also print
an error msg in the neutron-server.log file for easier detectibility
of the problem.

Change-Id: If884f90c4b1786cfc63d3e2ff2d66f92122258c2
Closes-Bug: #1432582

"}, {'created': '2015-03-24 10:55:05.000000000', 'message': "Add clock sync error detection on agent registration

For the server to determine if an agent is alive or not,
it depends on the agent's clock being mostly in sync with the server
clock. The neutron-server may reject and return the request if
there's a timestamp difference between the two nodes. Currently
there's no good way to detect this condition from the agent code.

This fix will improve the error detection
logic by throwing an exception back to the agent from the
neutron-server suggesting the cause of the error. It will also print
an error msg in the neutron-server.log file for easier detectibility
of the problem.

Change-Id: If884f90c4b1786cfc63d3e2ff2d66f92122258c2
Closes-Bug: #1432582

commit_message:
Add clock sync error detection on agent registration

For the server to determine if an agent is alive or not,
it depends on the agent's clock being mostly in sync with the server
clock. The neutron-server may reject and return the request if
there's a timestamp difference between the two nodes. Currently
there's no good way to detect this condition from the agent code.

This fix will improve the error handling
logic by writing an appropriate log in the neutron server's log
file for an early detection of the problem.

Change-Id: If884f90c4b1786cfc63d3e2ff2d66f92122258c2
Closes-Bug: #1432582

commit_message:
Add stable/kilo placeholder migrations

These provide a mechanism for us to backport any SQL migrations
we need to into stable/kilo, by ensuring we have 10 "spare" unused
migration numbers to backport into.

Change-Id: I51e411ac628ca98cbb3b60ddf9070d036bf12548

commit_message:
Make glance work reliably

Prior to this change, glance would occasionally never be able to find
keystone.  I don't know what the exact cause of the problem was, but
it affected only this container.  To resolve the issue, I copied another
container's crux and setup configuration.

I have seen this failure 3 or 4 times, but it is always very rare.

Change-Id: If4023c1fda6e35459ed65060d6d0e1a97b9d7f86

commit_message:
Allow additional heat environment files

Allows specifying additional/custom environment files so that, for example
parameter defaults for firstboot or post-deploy hooks can be specified.

Usage example:
export OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_ENVIRONMENT_FILES="-e foo.yaml"

Any number of additional files can be specified, with -e before each.

Change-Id: I8c1a88ef4286a347c5b0e6cd00b48ad23c4c9922

[{'created': '2015-04-14 17:56:46.000000000', 'message': "CentOS 7.1 image doesn't work with libvirt

The libvirt package has a dependency on systemd-libs and systemd,
while the centos 7.1 container installs systemd-container-libs
and systemd-container.  We don't need either of these systemd tools
but they reuslt in a broken build of the system if they are missing.

As is, the libvirt container will not build.

Change-Id: I8e5aac0e3a7e9d88a81733a3048971fe9d48ba56
"}]
commit_message:
CentOS 7.1 image doesn't work with libvirt

The libvirt package has a dependency on systemd-libs and systemd,
while the centos 7.1 container installs systemd-container-libs
and systemd-container.  We don't need either of these systemd tools
but they reuslt in a broken build of the system if they are missing.

As is, the libvirt container will not build.

Change-Id: I8e5aac0e3a7e9d88a81733a3048971fe9d48ba56

commit_message:
Allow _exec_ebtables to parse stderr

Some ebtables errors can be retried. Parse stderr and retry if the
error is the list of retriable errors.

Change-Id: I7618050b9ca28690b55c8c2424d04b40bd879442
Related-Bug: #1439355

commit_message:
JShint should ignore libraries

When undef and unused gets globally enabled, 3rd party libraries will fail.
We need to add a jshintginore file to ignore this folder.

Change-Id: I0ea8482b8b938bf89009063321b59b0a2cab3fde
Closes-bug: #1441821

commit_message:
puppet: implement MongoDB on controller nodes

This patch aims to configure MongoDB server on controller nodes with
Puppet.
It also create a default replicaset for Ceilometer, so MongoDB can be
highly available when multiple controllers are run.

Change-Id: I3c1ff06ebc3c9dac44fc790caaea711d0eba4bb7

commit_message:
Prevent unauthorized delete in versioned container

An authenticated user can delete the most recent version of any
versioned object who's name is known if the user has listing access
to the x-versions-location container. Only Swift setups with
allow_version setting are affected.

This patch closes this bug, tracked as CVE-2015-1856.

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Christian Schwede <info@cschwede.de>
Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>

Closes-Bug: 1430645

Change-Id: Icde494a9a2c851034813cbc3855a20335b643f09

Josh, I don't think simply using pippin here is enough.

Pippin is able to produce a list of packages that work for a given set of packages, at least in theory (it can still result in bugs due to incomplete requirements such as missing blocked releases etc). But because we install things differently in devstack we won't end up with the same list of dependencies as pippin lists.

On the other hand this is exactly what is needed to fully pin all dependencies  (requirements.in + requirements.txt and pip install --no-deps -r requirements.txt)

Also have you seen this: https://github.com/nvie/pip-tools/tree/master"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-02-02 22:33:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Josh want to explore the process of pinning all transitive dependencies in a separate patch set?  Long term that is the preferred solution, but I thought it would be more work because:

* make sure we build a good list of all dependencies
* change install logic everywhere to do pip install --no-deps
* add requirements.in and make requirements.txt exhaustive in every repo'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-02-02 22:37:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-02 23:11:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Verified-1

did anyone check if the some of the requirements actually make sense?  for instance, requests has a exclude that's outside of the range of the allowed.

+requests>=1.2.1,!=2.4.0,<=2.2.1

Also, was there discussion with packagers about this change?  It's making openstack very difficult to package for and I was already considering dropping it.  It seems that openstack can't figure out what dependencies it actually wants to use.

The capping is likely fine from a packager prospective, at least for the distro I'm packaging for (we have some flexibility for versions that get installed).  What's thrown me (and likely others) for a loop is that we had no input into this lockdown.  As long as the locking is done at the outset of the first release tag (juno/kilo/etc) it makes it easier to support.  This change in the middle is nearly impossible and made me come VERY close to removing all openstack services."}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2015-04-13 01:51:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

Also, what is the process of updating the freezes?

Is there a particular list where we can discuss packaging?

On thing that was nice about only setting the caps on known failures is that it made it MUCH easier to package for.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 17:38:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20:

For some more context see: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-February/057068.html

In short, this was a stop gap measure and we will be capping stable/kilo right away not in the middle of the cycle.


Also, what is the process of updating the freezes?  -we should update packages individually.  As you have already noticed https://review.openstack.org/#/c/161047/ is the more long term solution.

Is there a particular list where we can discuss packaging? -- Maybe just on the dev ML?

On thing that was nice about only setting the caps on known failures is that it made it MUCH easier to package for. As long as we don't have stable branches breaking underneath us and causing master to be blocked due to grenade that is great. But the previous process didn't work"}]

commit_message:
Cap explicit dependencies

pin all global-requirements with the version found in pip-freeze
along with a tool to generate the new requirements file

Issues:
* Some versions are only apt-get installable (suds 0.4.1)
* Not all packages are installed in our standard dsvm-tempest env
* Some versions are lower then the minimum requirement we previously had
  because python is awful (libvirt-python)
* Doesn't pin transitive dependencies
* library versions can vanish from pypi and still break us

Using pip-freeze file from a recently stable/juno neutron-full patch:
http://logs.openstack.org/40/154740/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full/c232cfe/logs/pip-freeze.txt.gz
(saved as pip-freezes.txt here for record keeping)

Grenade and tempest-full pip-freezes are different and do not work with
each other, so some tweaking is required.

Taking the installed library version from pip-freeze and use that as a
version cap.

Change-Id: Iaf48bb069fdd7a19d614ce44b86abd9977c5f0c0

commit_message:
Adding raw and clif formatted payload

It seems that cliff tries to force its hand when returning
an entity. The payload can be returned in a raw format; however,
it must also be returned in the cliff formatted way.

I have added both as a part of the payload option.

Change-Id: Ica3ed55e4d67347e14d5c313ca1aaced5d07ee14

commit_message:
Prevent unauthorized delete in versioned container

An authenticated user can delete the most recent version of any
versioned object who's name is known if the user has listing access
to the x-versions-location container. Only Swift setups with
allow_version setting are affected.

This patch closes this bug, tracked as CVE-2015-1856.

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Christian Schwede <info@cschwede.de>
Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>

Closes-Bug: 1430645

Change-Id: I74448c12bc4d4cd07d4300f452cf3dd6f66ca70a

commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: Id674f40532215788675c97a8fdfa91d4420347b3

commit_message:
Change NTP module

Change options:
* panic - panic is not boolean, it is integer, actually

Add options:
* tinker - disable or enable tinker
* minpoll - to change ntpd send packages frequency
* maxpoll - to change ntpd send packages frequency
* stepout - to change stepout interval

Change-Id: I8da3a129227061bd436e5343dfcceb8eb7a3aca0
Link to upstream fix: https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/MODULES-1925
Related-bug: #1430482
Related-bug: #1436373

commit_message:
Prevent unauthorized delete in versioned container

An authenticated user can delete the most recent version of any
versioned object who's name is known if the user has listing access
to the x-versions-location container. Only Swift setups with
allow_version setting are affected.

This patch closes this bug, tracked as CVE-2015-1856

commit_message:
Json DB fields export in json exporter fixed

In previous implementation we should additionaly call json.loads
on DB json fields for restoring object after export.
Casting of all DB fields to strings in row_as_dict has been removed.
Only unserializable fields converted now.
row_as_dict renamed to row_as_serializable_dict.

Change-Id: I190391f03068a8f932c6839ae6efb3c2f9fb3afd
Closes-Bug: #1443448

commit_message:
Add lock status into v2 API.

Add locked_by into v2 api because it's helpful for end user
to know the exact lock status of given instance.
V3(V2.1) API already has this information.
DocImpact
APIImpact

Implements: blueprint get-lock-status-of-instance

Change-Id: I089d56d5bbbd4e27ce70f7974d0a45e77dfcb984

commit_message:
Reduce excessive stacktraces in logs

No impact - just stops the API from dumping stack traces in the logs
when there is bad requests / invalid objects send to API

Change-Id: I020d0c05ea8b6c7973999d23078daf4365c79933

commit_message:
Checking if Trust exists should be DRY

Instead of duplicating the check for Trust existence in the
controller, move the check to the driver.

Change-Id: Id576ebe9922a70047b8276f372854e086295b6c4
Closes-Bug: #1443721

commit_message:
Open Liberty development

Bump pre-version in setup.cfg to formally open Liberty development.
Kilo release branch will be cut from the previous commit.

Change-Id: I8bb60f38956c44ae961e1da69f51e7f37c6beece

commit_message:
Add aborted and broken flags to sla checker

"aborted" flag will be used for saving information about situation when
task was stopped due to "abort-on-sla" option.

"broken" flag will be used for saving information about situtaion when
something gone wrong in context or runner.

Also, this patch removes two unstable scenarios.

Change-Id: I9e0c16c48af3643b15c8f5a241535bfb4540332c

commit_message:
add region_name to auth plugin parameters

If endpoint is not specified, then auth plugin will request to keystone
to get target endpoint, however, we don't provide region name for it,
this will cause critical issue in multiple region scenario.

Change-Id: I99ceafec25072988435018ca1affbd778ca9b22f
Closes-Bug: #1439553

commit_message:
Add SSL cert verification regression tests

A security bug (1357430) was introduced which meant that SSL certificate
verification was not occurring.

Add new tests which help prevent the 'requests' part of bug 115260
recurring.

Change-Id: Iaf56fd8bc34fa8f35c2fd7051f9f8424002352cf
Related-bug: 1357430
